segments.text: Major, and then I'm making Colonel Pearl.
Well, I've been a colonel until 56, which is about 12 years.
Of course, half the time I was out of the service.
When you come back in, they disregard everything and just make out like it never happened.
Of course, to you, that's a long time.
It begins to...
It's kind of devil.
It affects your ego.
It kind of affects everything.
You have to start rationalizing and hope that something comes of it.
But you can't do anything about the promotion system.
And we're doing it on service.
And your reserve time didn't count as service.
So you just step into a group with a different contemporary group.
But then after it happens, well,
Everything else, speed it up.
Sure.
But it was a long rest.
We've sort of talked around leadership for a while.
Let's turn to leadership now.
Would you define leadership for me?
No.
Oh, come on.
Nope.
I taught it, and I've learned it, but I'll define it.
I'll tell you.
I don't think any one person can define leadership.
Did you teach it to your ROTC?
Yeah.
What did you teach?
Well, I'd say that I taught the control and management of individuals to achieve an assigned mission.
That's about what it is.
I think I have expressed a number of different principles and beliefs to it.
Everybody's got to be handled differently if you've got the time and the space to do it.
You can't try to handle, in a technological world and technological business,
150 to 2,000 people all the same way because they don't all react the same way.
They don't all think the same way.
They're skilled at different abilities and professions.
And you may not be able to communicate with all of them at one time.
And you've got to realize it.
You have to recognize people as individuals and as human beings, and you've got to treat them that way.
And that's the reason I go back and say it's the control and the management of individuals to accomplish the mission.
And boy, that's a short statement, but it is broad and it's very involved.
What type of values do you later have?
Oh, man.
That's like a...
Scott is trustworthy, loyal, helpful, friendly, kind, obedient, cheerful, good, great, clean, and reverent.
Now we've got 12 of them out of us.
I think first and foremost, he's got to have enough self-confidence to believe that he can do the job that he has been given.
with the assets that he had been given to do the job with.

Even if he knows that he's short, even if he knows he's short in materials or short in people or short in certain specialties or specialists, he still has to have enough self-confidence that we're going to get the job done.
He doesn't want to be sent in a hurry by a subordinate, an old man

not with it you can't hack it he doesn't believe he can do it he doesn't believe we can do it and it won't get done along with that self-confidence there's got to be enough honesty that he's honest with himself and then i've got to qualify he's honest to the degree that he can afford to be with his people because sometimes he may have to
have to hide behind something to make them believe that they can do something that he doesn't really believe they can do.
But he's got to be respectful.
He's got to be respectful of himself.
He's got to be respectful of his subordinates.
We're talking
I'm talking in a position that may differ from a guy that commands a squadron of fighters or that commands a wing or something like that.
I'm talking again of leadership or management as I have practiced it since 1943 of being
being a staff officer, that I'm responsible for only a certain portion of what my boss is responsible for.
He's got a different role to play.
I know that.
In what way do you think it's different?
Well, he's got the whole ball of wax.
Well, isn't he still a manager?
Oh, very definitely so.
Sure.
Would you explain the difference?
Well...
So you feel there's different types of leaders?
Well, yeah.
See, I'm the guy that has to deal with the staff of... What have I had?
The staff of 8 to 120 people.
You know?
Certainly...
Get up to 120 people if you try to communicate with all of them.
It's a matter of control.

You still, when you go through and come through the office and stop, pass the time of day with him, check to see what he's doing, expose yourself to him to where they know this is the boss and this man, this is the greatest thing.
The guy that was here ahead of us never came back here.
The guy that was here ahead of you never came back here.
This is what I ran into, for instance, at the law command.
I inherited a deputy that the minute I said, hey, I want to go back to the sweatshop.
You don't want to go back there.
I said, I want to go back to the sweatshop.
And I want you to see that I go back there three times a week.
You never went back there.
I ain't the gentleman ahead of me.
My people are going to know who I am.
They're not going to be afraid to speak to me on the street or as I walk through that sweatshop.
And that's back where all the design is going on.
Sure.
The desks are sitting 12 feet apart, you know, and so on.
But the minute that started happening, people realized that, hey, this guy cares.
Efficiency improved.
We didn't have guys staying home sick.
You know...
was there.

Now, this commander that has got, that we're talking about, that's got me doing this, and me doing this, and me doing that, and then you've got these people out here, and each of them have got a boss.
He's got maybe eight, ten of us that are doing things for him.
He's got a different thing.
He's got a
Certainly he's got a responsibility to his boss, but his management of this whole operation, I don't say it's any simpler.
If it was simpler, he could have fewer stars than we did, but he doesn't have to deal with 120 people or 30 people or 40 people or so.
He has got experts, or we shouldn't be where we are.
And when he calls us and says,
When can you do it, and when can you have it done, or what do we have to do?
And we tell him, he's got to rely on us to believe it.
And his is a little more of every one of us, believe it or not, are generals.
And when he sits up there, I don't care whether he's got two or three stars, and he says, I want it done.
And we say, it'll be done.
But when we say this down
or some civilian and say, I want it done, you may or may not get that.
Okay, we've already passed this line.
We're now in that general officer's court, and when that boss or the general says, I've got to have it done by so-and-so, can you do it?
And you say, yes, then you've made a commitment, and you're going to have it done.
But these people below you haven't necessarily made that commitment.
You've got to earn that commitment.
You've got to earn that faith from them.
He didn't have to earn it from me.
When I reported in, I reported in as a dental officer.
And he said, it's there, you know, whether or not he knew me or not.
That's right.
Now, I say that it's a different type of management in charge.
When you're in that, you're back to that well-disciplined group that the old man says, okay,
My boss has told me we've got to have it done by the 28th.
You're going to have the materials ready for him by when?
All right.
It looks to me like we've got it made.
Now, y'all have committed to me.
It's going to be done.
But we didn't go around within our own staff and get a bunch of commitments before we came back up and made our commitments to him.
Well, there's different types of leaders in the military, it seems like.
There's sort of organizer-manager types, more like Eisenhower, and then there's the Patton type, more command leader or combat leader.
Yeah.
Well, sure, there's got to be.
And that's back to...
I think I've said it twice, this will be the third time, that we've got to have the tacticians and we've got to have the research development type.
These are different types of managers all together.

The tactician, he's got just as hard a job as this guy over here that's working the books and all the science and all the figures that can be worked to try to come out with something to make this guy a job.
You know what I mean?

Now, when you were teaching at A&M, and when you had, let's say that now as a general, they asked you to come back and give a talk to an 18-year-old court kid who wants to become a leader, and the topic was how to become a leader, what would you tell him?
Well.
If I was, you know, if I hadn't talked to them and they said, hey, how do you come here?
Well, if you're living the core experience and you are exposing yourself to the maximum of situations, attitudes, then you're going to
inherently absorb and put into your computer what you need to respond to whatever is put upon you
Remember I said the last place in the world that I call a leader is the guy that's out there marching close order command.
And knowing now that you're in fire control.
Now when you went through boot camp, some of those DIs that probably were under, I know that my son was under in the Marines,
That's right, but I don't necessarily call them the type of leaders that we're looking for, to take people into combat, to manage a critical phase of operations.
I'd have to know more about them than just their ability to take foot strong.
So my advice to the young man, and I have been back to A&M,
and talk to a military engineer.
Just keep exposing yourself.
Boy, get in every situation that you can and learn all that you can about life.
And I'll tell you, this is not original with me because I don't know whether you have heard of this Spencer J. Buchanan that I spoke to.
I used to go to class, and this was after the war, when I went back.
And Spencer Jay would sit, and though some of us were veterans, most of the class would be cadets, because most of the veterans were not going back to study engineering.
I don't know why.
I think they went over to some of the other schools.
But I've been in class when Spencer Jay just saw a mechanic book and folded it up and said, we'll talk about that next time.
What we're going to talk about today
life and how to get along.
He's a retired Corps of Engineers Brigadier General.
One of the most outstanding men I've ever known.
He helped me in my world for my master's degree.
Somebody asked me a question and I didn't know how to answer it.
It wasn't a technical question at all.
They said, what in the world is an Air Force major doing at Texas A&M studying permafrost?
I sat there and I thought, how the hell am I going to answer a question like that?
And he waited a few minutes and he said, the state of Texas last year incurred a loss of a million dollars.
Cross damage alone
for their highways.
Permafrost is an allied phenomenon, worse than this frost.
It underlays many of the bases and installations of our armed forces.
This officer has taken the time to learn something scientifically about it.
I suggest that we hear his review.
That's it.
Now, if we can, I said, well, from then on, smooth sailing.
But how are we going to answer a question?
What are you doing studying permafrost at A&M?
We don't have permafrost at A&M.
Certainly don't.
Did you know General Rudder?
No, I can't see that.
Let's talk a little bit about the changes that have happened at A&M since you were there, especially the changes in the 1960s, which fundamentally altered the type of institution.
And I'd like to have your opinions on some of them.
First, the end of the mandatory court.
Well, I guess I showed my ignorance when I say I don't know what the mandatory court started with.
Because the law, from what I know about it, did not make the military mandatory.
And therefore, it must have been made mandatory by either the state or the school.
But I don't think the law made military mandatory.
Not the federal law.
That's what I'm talking about, the federal law.
But the school regulations.
But the point is that before the early 1960s, everybody who went to A&M was either a veteran or in the Corps.
And that was changed by
by General Rutter, and now, of course, you know, there's a couple thousand corpsmen and there's about 30,000 so-called civilians.
And I was wondering, what's your opinion of that change?
What is your opinion of that change?
Well, I'm sure that...
I think it's certainly probably given the opportunity of the college to go into the university and the university to continue to enlarge.
Were it mandatory for the student who was not a veteran
belong to the core, I doubt that the institution would be of its size and its stature as important as that.
Do you think that's a good, I mean, do you think it's a good change that every, that the students, that they don't have to be former, or do you think it's negative, or?
Under the
The attitudes of our society today, I think it's probably served the betterment of the institution.
Whether it's served the betterment of the armed services, I would probably have to say no.
But the institution, I think, is probably the betterment of the institution.
Another one of the major changes, of course, is allowing women at A&M.
What's your opinion of that?
Should have been there in 1936.
I would rather have had one of your roommates than one of the roommates I met.
That's the way you felt when it was changed?
Well, my first reaction was, gee, what's going to happen?
But I think it was inevitable.
I happen to be of a minority group, even in Kiwanis.
Whenever I'm a delegate to a national convention that I have been to three of, and it's voted as to whether we will permit women into Kiwanis, I'm always going to vote yes.
We never seem to do it.
One of these days we will.
Why do you think you vote yes?
I beg your pardon?
Why do you think that you vote yes?
I don't know why I vote yes.

Because I think that we've got professional women that want to be in our service organization that are just as capable of doing service to their community and to the people in need in their community as the men are.
That doesn't say to me that Mrs. Jones' housewife is the type that ought to be a member of Kiwanis just because she's a woman.

But if the CPA that has his office, Pat Booker, is a member of Kiwanis, and we've got a female lawyer down the street that wants to be, and she's a practicing lawyer, and is willing to give her time and efforts to service to the community, I think that that's what we want.
That's what we need.
But how can you get some of these old diehards
Now I turn right around and so happens I'm on Master Basin and Shrine.
That's something entirely different.
That is an organization that is built strictly for men and it is not necessarily built to serve the community.
And it's not based on professionalism.
It's a paternal organization.
But what about during, of course, during the time that you were in the Air Force, there were a number of...
In the Air Force?
When you were in the service in the Air Force, there was a great increase in the number of women into the Air Force, and still is today.
I was wondering about your opinions of that.

It doesn't bother me in the least, because when I was the Director of Personnel in the 80th General of the 302nd Transport Wing, I had a WAF captain in Ferris and a number of WAFs, not WAFs, WACs, because we were still armed.
WAC captains and a number of WACs were in my organization doing just as good a job as the men.
Well, what's your opinion of drafting women today?
Drafting women?
Yeah, this is a new...
Boy, you've had to put that question in since you started this research.
I don't know, I, Maudie and I, my wife and I have talked about this one for a while and I haven't really reached a position on that as to whether they should be subjected to the draft.
I think there's a certain
state or status that can be maintained that permits one to volunteer but does not necessarily require one at that section to mandatorily serve.
One is not necessarily directive or inherent upon the other.
I just, I have not come to a real, I'm leaning a little bit towards they ought not be mandatory.
You haven't quite made up your mind on that.
Of course, another of the major changes at A&M in the mid-1960s was, well, by 1968, was allowing blacks to enter A&M.
And it had been a segregated institution for almost its first 100 years.
And I was wondering what you thought about allowing blacks in.
Long overdue.
Long overdue.
say and this is not qualifying my statement of saying long my feeling towards black has certainly definitely certainly results from long-term service i am sure that and i uh
gone to some other institution, served my time during the war, gotten out and stayed in Texas, maybe even South Texas, that I would probably not have the strong feeling that I have right now.
That I think that we
We're going to do wrong if we don't make it even more open and if we don't do something to, well, let's push that.
If we don't open it even more and encourage more.
And I'll even strengthen it by saying,
The year that I was president of my Kiwanis Club, which was whatever date that said up there, there were... 1977, 1978.
Okay, there were four, there were 14 clubs in our division.
And I was the first club, first president to ever bring blacks in.
club in this area.
There are a lot of clubs in Texas, Oklahoma that are predominantly black.
There were very few that had just one or two of them.
And I brought three blacks into our club during my year.
I brought a retired Chief Master Sergeant who is still in our club and is Secretary of our club.
I brought a local postmaster from Universal City, and I brought a major active duty Air Force from Randolph.
He was a professional individual who wanted to be an Aquarian and had every right to be an Aquarian.
Boy, I was one, and you made me one.
Was there resistance?
Not from my own club, but from others.
Are you sure you all know what you're doing here?
But they're still there.
Was there hard feelings?
No.
Just a little uneasiness, you might say.
But how do they, are they still there?
I mean, are relations?
Two of them are still in the club.
The postmaster has dropped out, but we still have good relations with him.
I don't know whether you're familiar with them, but boy, some of those guys, I talked to one over in Galveston County a couple of weeks ago, and they have a harder time than some of the military.
They put them on some of the dirty studies, and a lot of them don't make as much as some of the carriers that work for them.
And they work longer hours.
Yeah, it's crazy.
So you think that it was long overdue to have blacks at A&M.
I was wondering, you were in the service in the early 1950s.
You were called back during Korea when President Truman integrated, desegregated the armed forces.
And of course, the Air Force was integrated at this time.
And I was wondering about your opinions of that.
Long overdue.
Well, we had black troops at Mobile when we were forming these air depot groups.
Yeah, back in the war.
That's right.
And all that we could do is either form quartermaster truck companies and then keep them all in that little truck company or platoon.
That wasn't an integrated option.
But it just makes the whole damn situation
organization and establishment.
Just on paper and physically more difficult, but then you ask the question, why should it be to start with?
So you think then that by having qualified women and qualified blacks in the service and integrated positions, co-ed positions, it makes the Air Force and the other services more efficient?
than to have segregated units?
Is that what I'm, is that what you meant to say?
I mean.
Well, I would, yeah, let's say as efficient, or it does not affect the efficiency.
Okay, it does not affect the efficiency.
I don't say that it's an improvement.
It may or may not be.
When I was chief of the master planning branch, for instance, there in Washington, my number one secretary was his wife.
She was outstanding.
Heather was one of the best damn secretaries that I've ever met.
Now you said during these two days of conversations that
You're a very conservative Republican, yet at the same time, on some social issues like women and blacks, you don't seem very conservative at all.
Or am I putting words in your mouth?
No, no.
How can you call yourself a conservative Republican then?
I mean, doesn't it, do you see a problem there?
No, I don't.
No, I don't think so.
Maybe it's because I put a closer association to the socialists and the liberals and consider them probably closer to each other than to the conservatives.
So you're talking more economically, then?
No, that's right.
I don't believe in a lot of the
social programs.
And most of the social programs, as far as I'm concerned, have been sponsored and endorsed and kept alive by the liberals once they're established.
And I don't know, maybe that's where I kind of draw the dividing line to the definition.
OK, back to A&M then.
Since the 1930s when you attended to, well, the early 50s when you taught there and today, do you think that it has changed in a positive way or a negative way?
Do you think it's a better institution today than it was then?
I think it's definitely a better institution.
Well,
I don't think you have to go back that far.
Well, when I got my master's, minor in business.
Right now, I couldn't even tell you what school the business department was in because it wasn't a school of its own.
You know, it was just stuck away somewhere.
I bet it, I bet when I was at the time I was in school as an undergrad, 37 to 41,
I bet there weren't over eight different history courses thrown together, if that makes sense.
And like I said earlier and somewhere yesterday, it's strong points were agricultural and some were engineering, and yet at that,
some of its engineering wasn't very highly acceptable.
But I think that they've come a long, long way.
And just when the different schools are put in rank and file, either, not within Texas, because I think we'll always be A&M or Texas sitting on top, but across the sound or across the nation,
It's a national competitive medicine.
Oh, I certainly should not neglect that, veterinary medicine, because at one time, there were only two places in Ohio State that picked it in, if anybody would think about that.
I'm sure there's more than that now, but...
Since it has changed definitely from, even this thing, the institution has changed from a college to a university.
It's certainly got to improve or somebody's just using words and kidding themselves.
My older son would have given anything in the world to go to A&M.
Boy, he researched and studied what all was available.
He just said, there is absolutely no way that I can go to Texas A&M.
and get what I want to know in international relations.
It is not there.
The faculty is not there, and the courses are not there.
And you've got to have both.
But times have changed.
Yesterday I had a wonderful luncheon last Friday with the head of the MBA, dean of the MBA here in town Friday.
one of the leading Aggies, had a luncheon for him out at North Country Club, just so that he could become acquainted with a number of his contemporaries.
He had 40 guests, and I think 37 had on Aggie rings.
Two had on Texas rings, and one had on a West Point ring.
Well we've covered a number of topics and I was wondering, because you're the expert on your life, I was wondering if I've left anything out that you'd like to put on tape.
Is there anything else that, because I'm out of questions.
Yeah.
Oh, if it's a format, no.

I think that as we've gone through here, I have, other than when we were going to lunch, we've actually said nothing about some of the military honors and things like that that have accrued to the period.
Well, let's talk about those.
I think we mentioned the
the Silver Beaver and the Boy Scout, which is probably the one outside of the military, but from an organization.
The Distinguished Service Medal that was awarded at the time of my retirement, that is the highest award that can be given by any of the military services in time of peace.
The one next to it is the Legion of Merit.
I managed to pick that thing up, no matter what I call it, three times.
How did you get to Distinguished Service?
That was the working department.
And I am listed in VUVU in America and VUVU in Engineering.
I know how I got into engineering, but the slightest idea is that I got new to the earth.
Which one of the medals do you value the most?
Oh, certainly the extended service medal.
It's the highest, and that's where you would, you know.
In fact, a lot of them are caught here, but it's not my own country's medal.
But I have a lot of fun.
If I go to France, I wear the little boutonniere that signifies that he has been awarded the Croix de Guerre.
And of course, the Frenchman will see it.
I've enjoyed the retirement, of course.
You can call it retirement, but I'm still waiting
really know what it means, I guess.
We have a wonderful situation here that the San Antonio area, I don't know whether any of the others have told you about it, but
Each year, two different organizations call all the reserve officers to a full day of briefings and socializing.
The morning is filled with briefings.
At lunch in the afternoon, it's filled with golf.
And it's either to Kelly Air Force Base, which is the logistics command.
You learn all about, technically, all the aircraft and all the files and stuff.
And the other is Dr. Randolph, where you learn all about the personnel problems and the training of people and so on.
And they call any of the Air Force officers in the area into these meetings, and they're pretty well attended.
There'll be 50 to 60 generals in each one of them.
It certainly helps us keep abreast of what's going on.
Though most that are in attendance are no longer eligible for RICO, some are.
When you pass the 60 line, you begin to go off.
I'm sure they can reach out and get you to have a war, but right now there is no policy for RICO until beyond the age of 60.
I guess that does it.
That's about it.
Thank you very much, gentlemen.
I really appreciate this opportunity to chat with you.
